---
import { slug } from 'github-slugger';
import type { GetStaticPaths, InferGetStaticPropsType } from 'astro';
import ArticleLayout from '@layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';

// Mock blog content data
const blogPosts = [
  {
    slug: 'getting-started-with-v0',
    collection: 'blog',
    data: {
      title: 'Getting Started with v0: A Complete Beginner\'s Guide',
      description: 'Learn how to use v0 by Vercel to generate production-ready UI components using AI.',
      publishDate: new Date('2026-04-10'),
      updatedDate: new Date('2026-04-12'),
      author: 'John Doe',
      category: 'tutorials',
      tags: ['v0', 'tutorial', 'beginner', 'AI'],
      image: '/assets/blog/getting-started.jpg',
      featured: true,
      readingTime: 8,
    },
    body: `
# Getting Started with v0

v0 by Vercel is an AI-powered UI generation platform that allows you to create production-ready React components using natural language prompts.

## What is v0?

v0 (pronounced "v-zero") is Vercel's latest innovation in AI-assisted development. It uses large language models to generate React components with Tailwind CSS styling based on your text descriptions.

## Getting Started

### Step 1: Create an Account

Head over to [v0.dev](https://v0.dev?ref=v0affiliate) and sign up for a free account. You can get started with the free tier which includes 10 generations per day.

### Step 2: Write Your First Prompt

Once logged in, you'll see a simple text input. Try describing the component you want to build:

\`\`\`
Create a pricing card with three tiers, featuring a monthly and annual billing toggle.
\`\`\`

### Step 3: Iterate and Refine

v0 allows you to refine the generated component with follow-up prompts. You can ask it to:
- Change colors
- Add animations
- Modify layout
- Add interactive elements

## Pro Tips

1. **Be Specific**: The more detailed your prompt, the better the output.
2. **Use Iterations**: Don't expect perfection on the first try. Use follow-up prompts.
3. **Learn from Output**: Study the generated code to improve your own skills.

## Conclusion

v0 is a powerful tool that can significantly speed up your UI development workflow. Start with the free tier and upgrade when you're ready for more features.

> **Ready to get started?** [Sign up for v0 today](https://v0.dev?ref=v0affiliate) and transform your development workflow!
    `,
  },
  {
    slug: 'v0-vs-cursor-ai',
    collection: 'blog',
    data: {
      title: 'v0 vs Cursor AI: Which is Better for UI Development?',
      description: 'An in-depth comparison of two leading AI-powered development tools.',
      publishDate: new Date('2026-04-08'),
      updatedDate: new Date('2026-04-09'),
      author: 'Jane Smith',
      category: 'reviews',
      tags: ['v0', 'cursor', 'comparison', 'AI', 'review'],
      image: '/assets/blog/v0-vs-cursor.jpg',
      featured: false,
      readingTime: 12,
    },
    body: `
# v0 vs Cursor AI: Comprehensive Comparison

Both v0 and Cursor AI promise to accelerate your development workflow using AI, but they take very different approaches.

## Overview

### v0 by Vercel
- **Focus**: UI component generation
- **Output**: React + Tailwind CSS code
- **Best for**: Frontend developers, designers

### Cursor AI
- **Focus**: Full codebase assistance
- **Output**: Any programming language
- **Best for**: Full-stack developers

## Key Differences

| Feature | v0 | Cursor AI |
|---------|-----|-----------|
| UI Generation | ✓ Excellent | △ Limited |
| Code Editing | △ Basic | ✓ Excellent |
| Full-Stack | ✗ No | ✓ Yes |
| Free Tier | ✓ Yes | ✗ No |

## When to Use v0

Choose v0 when you need to:
- Rapidly prototype UI components
- Generate consistent design systems
- Create responsive layouts

## When to Use Cursor AI

Choose Cursor when you need to:
- Work on backend code
- Refactor existing codebases
- Debug complex issues

## Our Verdict

For **UI-focused development**, v0 is the clear winner. Its specialized AI models produce better component code and integrate seamlessly with the Vercel ecosystem.

[**Try v0 for free →**](https://v0.dev?ref=v0affiliate)
    `,
  },
];

export function getStaticPaths(): InferGetStaticPropsType<typeof getStaticPaths>[] {
  return blogPosts.map((post) => ({
    params: { slug: post.slug },
    props: { post },
  }));
}

const { post } = Astro.props;
const { title, description, image, publishDate, updatedDate, author, tags, readingTime, body } = post.data;
---

<ArticleLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  image={image}
  publishedTime={publishDate.toISOString()}
  modifiedTime={updatedDate?.toISOString()}
  author={author}
  category={post.data.category}
  tags={tags}
  readingTime={readingTime}
>
  <Fragment set:html={body} />
</ArticleLayout>
